{"title_page": "Department of the Director of Dockyards", "text_new": "{{Infobox government agency\n|agency_name     =  Department of the Director of Dockyards\n|motto           =\n|logo            = File:Naval Ensign of Great Britain (1707-1800).svg\n|logo_width      = 150px\n|logo_caption    = \n|seal            = \n|seal_width      =\n|seal_caption    =\n|preceding1    =  [[Surveyor of the Navy|Department of the Surveyor of the Navy]]\n|jurisdiction  = [[Government of the United Kingdom]]\n|headquarters  = [[Admiralty]]<br />[[London]]\n|formed          = 1872\n|dissolved       = 1964\n|superseding     = Dockyards and Fleet Maintenance Department\n|employees       =\n|budget          =\n|chief1_name     = Director-General of Dockyards\n|chief1_position = \n|chief2_name     = Director of Dockyards\n|chief2_position = \n|chief3_name     = Director of Fleet Maintenance\n|chief3_position = \n|chief4_name     = Director of Marine Services\n|chief4_position = \n|parent_department   = [[Admiralty]]\n|child1_agency   =\n|website         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Department of the Director of Dockyards''',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Archives|first1=The National|title=Records of Dockyards|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C721|website=discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|publisher=National Archives, 1690-1981, ADM 312|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> also known as the '''Dockyard Branch'''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Haas|first1=J. M.|title=A Management Odyssey: The Royal Dockyards, 1714-1914|date=1994|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=9780819194619|page=190|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GGIIJbXqLucC&pg=PA190&lpg=PA190&dq=Dockyard+Branch,+Admiralty&source=bl&ots=8olOJ2uydM&sig=yHU7FH0-QiwhDBOE1MZxmnVtOWA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinpvXSirXVAhWMsY8KHZ76AocQ6AEIOjAD#v=onepage&q=Dockyard%20Branch%2C%20Admiralty&f=false|language=en}}</ref> and later as the '''Dockyards and Fleet Maintenance Department''',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Archives|first1=The National|title=Director General Dockyards and Fleet Maintenance Department: report on Vote 8 Ship Drawing Offices at HM Dockyard, Chatham, Kent|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C11194424|website=discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|publisher=National Archives, 1 Jan 1961 - 31 Dec, ADM 312/4|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> was the [[Admiralty|British Admiralty department]] responsible from 1872 to 1964 for civil administration of dockyards, the building of ships, the maintenance and repair of ships at dockyards and factories, and the supervision of all civil dockyard personnel.\n\n==History==\nOriginally, responsibility for the civil management of [[Royal Navy Dockyard]]s lay with the [[Navy Board]], and in particular the [[Surveyor of the Navy]] who supervised the Navy Board's resident commissioners of the navy based at each individual yard. Following the abolition of the Navy Board in 1832, responsibility for administration of the yards passed to the [[Board of Admiralty]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Winfield|first1=Rif|title=British Warships in the Age of Sail 1817-1863: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates|date=30 April 2014|publisher=Seaforth Publishing|isbn=9781473849624|page=399|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=imFEBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA399&dq=abolition+of+the+Navy+Board+in+1832&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwie4qTFk7PVAhUYR48KHdOwDg04ChDoAQgjMAA#v=onepage&q=abolition%20of%20the%20Navy%20Board%20in%201832&f=false}}</ref> The resident commissioners were replaced by yard [[Admiral-superintendent|superintendents]], however they were primarily responsible for military administration of the yards.\n\nThe ''Surveyor of the Navy'' survived the re-organisation until 1869, when his office was merged with that of the [[Third Sea Lord|Third Naval Lord]] to become [[Controller of the Navy]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Archives|first1=The National|title=Records of the Surveyor of the Navy and successors|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C712|website=discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|publisher=National Archives, 1620-1979|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> Between 1850 and 1861, the dockyards had been subject to an investigation into management practices; the committee responsible for the investigation concluded that under the existing system was completely inefficient.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Coats|first1=Dr Anne|last2=Davies|first2=Dr David|title=20TH CENTURY NAVAL DOCKYARDS: DEVONPORT AND PORTSMOUTH CHARACTERISATION REPORT|url=https://content.historicengland.org.uk/images-books/publications/twentieth-century-naval-dockyards-devonport-portsmouth-characterisation-report/part1-twentieth-century-naval-dockyards-devonport-portsmouth-characterisation.pdf/|website=Historic England|publisher=Naval Dockyards Society, part 1, p.2, 2015|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> In 1872, to ease the burden of work on the Controller and to action reforms suggested by the inquiry, a '''Surveyor of Dockyards''' was appointed to answer these criticisms. He was originally supervised by the [[Director of Naval Construction]], who was responsible for both design and construction, and also dockyard work.\n\nIn December 1885 the post of ''Surveyor of Dockyards'' was abolished and replaced by a '''Director of Dockyards'''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brassey|first1=Earl Thomas Allnutt|title=Brassey's Annual: The Armed Forces Year-book|date=1909|publisher=Praeger Publishers|page=68}}</ref>  The new Director was instructed to visit the dockyards frequently, \"for the purpose of conferring personally with the superintendents and officers in regard to the ships and works in progress.\" <ref>{{cite book|last1=Hamilton|first1=Sir Vesey|title=The Constitution, Character and Functions of the Board of Admiralty and the Civil Departments it Directs|date=1896|publisher=George Bell and Sons|isbn=9781150465000|chapter=IV}}</ref> However, inefficiencies led to a recommendation by [[George Robinson, 1st Marquess of Ripon|George Robinson, Lord Ripon]] in which he suggested there should be a separation of the functions and duties of the naval design and construction branches, which would remain distinct from each other,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Leggett|first1=Don|title=Shaping the Royal Navy: Technology, Authority and Naval Architecture, C.1830-1906|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780719090288|page=217|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4S6hDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA218&lpg=PA218&dq=lord+ripon+admiralty+reforms&source=bl&ots=-VYrbHcOMX&sig=Oh7HLvXjJ2D4LTNDiYxHNlPBHnQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwir1pXPjLPVAhUZTo8KHQEiDwQQ6AEIPTAE#v=onepage&q=lord%20ripon%20admiralty%20reforms&f=false|language=en}}</ref> and that the branches should both coordinate and operate a sort of checks and balance system.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Leggett|first1=Don|title=Shaping the Royal Navy: Technology, Authority and Naval Architecture, C.1830-1906|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780719090288|page=217|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4S6hDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA218&lpg=PA218&dq=lord+ripon+admiralty+reforms&source=bl&ots=-VYrbHcOMX&sig=Oh7HLvXjJ2D4LTNDiYxHNlPBHnQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwir1pXPjLPVAhUZTo8KHQEiDwQQ6AEIPTAE#v=onepage&q=lord%20ripon%20admiralty%20reforms&f=false|language=en}}</ref> A set of instructions issued on 28 May 1886 communicated that the Director of Dockyards would no longer be subordinate to the Director of Naval Construction.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hamilton|first1=Sir Vesey|title=The Constitution, Character and Functions of the Board of Admiralty and the Civil Departments it Directs|date=1896|publisher=George Bell and Sons|isbn=9781150465000|chapter=IV}}</ref> Instead, he was made solely responsible to the Controller for the building of ships at dockyards, and for the maintenance and repair of ships, of boats, and of all steam machinery in ships, boats, dockyards, and factories.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Committee on Naval Affairs|first1=United States. Congress. House|title=Hearings on the Proposed Reorganization of the Navy Department Before the Committee on Naval Affairs of the House of Representatives [December 16, 1909 to February 17, 1910|date=1910|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|page=727}}</ref> In 1892 the post of Director of Dockyards was changed to ''Director of Dockyards and Works'' until 1913, when it was again renamed to ''Director of Dockyards and Repair''.\n\nDuring and after World War One, from 1917 to 1919, further restructuring with the Admiralty took place with the creation of the post of [[Deputy Controller for Dockyards and Shipbuilding]], to which the Director of Dockyards and Repairs would now report to. The department under this name would remain in place until 1957, when it was renamed '''Dockyards and Fleet Maintenance Department''' under the control of a [[Director-General]] until 1964.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Archives|first1=The National|title=Records of Dockyards|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C721|website=discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|publisher=National Archives, 1690-1981, ADM 312|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> Following the merger of the Admiralty into a new and much larger Ministry of Defence under the Navy Department, it was again renamed as the '''Department of Dockyards and Maintenance''' until 1968.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Archives|first1=The National|title=Records of Dockyards|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C721|website=discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|publisher=National Archives, 1690-1981, ADM 312|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> In 1969, overall responsibility for dockyards changed, and now came under the control of a new [[Chief Executive, Royal Dockyards]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Gordon|title=Royal Navy, including Administration, 1961-1970|url=http://www.naval-history.net/xGM-Ops-Events1961-70.htm|website=www.naval-history.net|publisher=Gordon Smith, 10 July 2011|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> who was head of the [[Royal Dockyards Management Board]].<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons 27 July 1971|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1971/jul/27/royal-dockyards|website=Hansard}}</ref>\n\n==Duties==\nA director's duties included:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hamilton|first1=Sir Vesey|title=The Constitution, Character and Functions of the Board of Admiralty and the Civil Departments it Directs|date=1896|publisher=George Bell and Sons|isbn=9781150465000|chapter=IV}}</ref>\n* assisting the Controller in the preparation of the estimates for plant and machinery required for all naval establishments;\n* exercising control of naval expenditure at all home yards;\n* exercising control of naval expenditure at all overseas yards;\n* general management of the dockyards at home and the naval yards abroad;\n* managing the economical performance of the dockyards at home and the naval yards abroad;\n* preparing annual programmes of work (subject to approval in the dockyards at home and the naval yards abroad;\n* preparing of the Navy Estimates, to determine the work to be done in the dockyards;\n* regulating the number, appropriation, and pay of the men, and the supply of necessary materials through the Director of Stores, in accordance with the approved shipbuilding programme;\n* submitting proposals relative to necessary works to be carried out in the yards by the Department of the Director of Works;\n* superintending the building of ships and boats of all classes;\n* superintending the proper maintenance and repairing of ships and their machinery, and the keeping of vessels up to the approved standard; and \n* supplying relevant machinery and appliances and provide instruction of the use of both in the yards and factories, as well as in the victualling yards.\n\n==Incumbents==\nHead of Department included:\n\n===Surveyor of Dockyards===\n* Sir Frederick Barnes, 1872 - December 1885) <ref>{{cite book|last1=Haas|first1=J. M.|title=A Management Odyssey: The Royal Dockyards, 1714-1914|date=1994|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=9780819194619|page=128|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GGIIJbXqLucC&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&dq=Admiralty,+Surveyor+of+Dockyards&source=bl&ots=8olOI4sxeP&sig=-Bwmaj9efFDcHnJL2SaHB1dHdcE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwihl6fs2LLVAhVF6Y8KHW3IBHIQ6AEIUDAG#v=onepage&q=Admiralty%2C%20Surveyor%20of%20Dockyards&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Director of Dockyards===\n* [[Sir Frederick Barnes]], December 1885 - February 1886  <ref>{{cite book|last1=Haas|first1=J. M.|title=A Management Odyssey: The Royal Dockyards, 1714-1914|date=1994|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=9780819194619|page=128|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GGIIJbXqLucC&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&dq=Admiralty,+Surveyor+of+Dockyards&source=bl&ots=8olOI4sxeP&sig=-Bwmaj9efFDcHnJL2SaHB1dHdcE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwihl6fs2LLVAhVF6Y8KHW3IBHIQ6AEIUDAG#v=onepage&q=Admiralty%2C%20Surveyor%20of%20Dockyards&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\n* Dr. [[Francis Elgar]], February 1886 - 1892 <ref>{{cite book|last1=Stationary|first1=Office|title=The Navy List|date=1888|publisher=John Murray and Son|page=301}}</ref>\n\n===Director of Dockyards and Works===\n* [[Sir James Williamson]], 1892 - July 1905) <ref>{{cite book|last1=Stationary|first1=Office|title=The Navy List|date=1892|publisher=John Murray and Son|page=349}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Haas|first1=J. M.|title=A Management Odyssey: The Royal Dockyards, 1714-1914|date=1994|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=9780819194619|page=171|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GGIIJbXqLucC&pg=PA171&dq=James+Williamson+Director+of+Dockyards&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjonrOFmbPVAhVIq48KHR7BAlkQ6AEIJDAA#v=onepage&q=James%20Williamson%20Director%20of%20Dockyards&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Sir James B. Marshall]], July 1905- March 1913 <ref>{{cite web|last1=Harley|first1=Simon|last2=Lovell|first2=Tony|title=Director of Dockyards and Repair (Royal Navy) - The Dreadnought Project|url=http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Director_of_Dockyards_and_Repair_(Royal_Navy)|website=dreadnoughtproject.org|publisher=Harley and Lovell, 18 June 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Director of Dockyards and Repair===\n* [[Sir James B. Marshall]], March 1913- April 1917 <ref>{{cite web|last1=Harley|first1=Simon|last2=Lovell|first2=Tony|title=Director of Dockyards and Repair (Royal Navy) - The Dreadnought Project|url=http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Director_of_Dockyards_and_Repair_(Royal_Navy)|website=dreadnoughtproject.org|publisher=Harley and Lovell, 18 June 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n* Vice-Admiral Sir [[Laurence Eliot Power]], 1 June 1917 \u2013 31 March 1923 <ref>{{cite web|last1=Harley|first1=Simon|last2=Lovell|first2=Tony|title=Director of Dockyards and Repair (Royal Navy) - The Dreadnought Project|url=http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Director_of_Dockyards_and_Repair_(Royal_Navy)|website=dreadnoughtproject.org|publisher=Harley and Lovell, 18 June 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n* Admiral Sir. [[Brian Barttelot|Brian H. F. Barttelot]], March, 1923 \u2013 1 March 1928 <ref>{{cite web|last1=Harley|first1=Simon|last2=Lovell|first2=Tony|title=Director of Dockyards and Repair (Royal Navy) - The Dreadnought Project|url=http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Director_of_Dockyards_and_Repair_(Royal_Navy)|website=dreadnoughtproject.org|publisher=Harley and Lovell, 18 June 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n* Admiral Sir. [[Percy Addison|Albert P. Addison]], 1 March 1928 \u2013 1 May 1937 <ref>{{cite web|last1=Harley|first1=Simon|last2=Lovell|first2=Tony|title=Director of Dockyards and Repair (Royal Navy) - The Dreadnought Project|url=http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Director_of_Dockyards_and_Repair_(Royal_Navy)|website=dreadnoughtproject.org|publisher=Harley and Lovell, 18 June 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n* Vice-Admiral Sir. [[Cecil Ponsonby Talbot|Cecil P. Talbot]], 1 May 1937 \u2013 20 December 1946 <ref>{{cite web|last1=Harley|first1=Simon|last2=Lovell|first2=Tony|title=Director of Dockyards and Repair (Royal Navy) - The Dreadnought Project|url=http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Director_of_Dockyards_and_Repair_(Royal_Navy)|website=dreadnoughtproject.org|publisher=Harley and Lovell, 18 June 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n* Admiral Sir. [[Claud Barry|Claud B. Barry]], 20 December 1946 - 31 December 1951 <ref>{{cite book|last1=Government|first1=H.M.|title=The Navy List|date=May 1951|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|page=344|chapter=Admiralty Department and Staff}}</ref>\n* Vice-Admiral. [[Sir. W. York La Roche Beverley]], 31 December 1951 - 19 July 1954 <ref>{{cite book|last1=Government|first1=H.M.|title=The Navy List|date=May 1954|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|page=428|chapter=Admiralty Department and Staff}}</ref>\n* Vice-Admiral, Sir. [[Gordon Hubback|A. Gordon V. Hubback]], 19 July 1954 - 31 December 1957 <ref>{{cite book|last1=Government|first1=H.M.|title=The Navy List|date=April 1956|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|page=1269|chapter=Admiralty Department and Staff}}</ref>\n\n===Director-General of Dockyards and Maintenance===\n* Rear-Admiral, [[Peter Pelly|Peter D. H. R. Pelly]], 2 January 1958 <ref>{{cite book|last1=Government|first1=H.M.|title=The Navy List|date=18 January 1958|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|page=1246|chapter=Admiralty Department and Staff}}</ref> - December 1959\n* Vice-Admiral [[Sir. Reginald Thomas Sandars]], December 1959 <ref>{{cite book|last1=Government|first1=H.M.|title=The Navy List|date=April 1962 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|page=927|chapter=Admiralty Department and Staff}}</ref> - 19 May 1962 <ref>{{cite web|last1=Houterman|first1=J.N.|title=Royal Navy (RN) Officers 1939-1945  --  S|url=http://www.unithistories.com/officers/RN_officersS.html|website=unithistories.com|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Rear-Admiral W. A. Haynes, 19 May 1962 - April 1964 <ref>{{cite book|last1=Government|first1=H.M.|title=The Navy List|date=April 1968|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|page=546|chapter=Admiralty Department and Staff}}</ref>\n:''Note: RADM Haynes remained as Director-General, Dockyards and Maintenance with the new Ministry of Defence from May 1964 until 1969.''\n\n==Structure of Department==\n:As of Spring 1962 <ref>{{cite book|last1=Government|first1=H.M.|title=The Navy List|date=April 1962|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|pages=927\u2013928|chapter=Admiralty Departments and Staff}}</ref>\n* Office of the Director-General Dockyards and Maintenance ---------- Office of the Civil Assistant to the Director-General Dockyards and Maintenance\n** Divisions\n*** Dockyards\n**** Construction Departments\n**** Draughting Departments\n**** Electrical Departments\n**** Engineering Departments\n**** Maintenance Departments\n**** Salvage Departments\n**** Training Sections\n'''Dockyard Division'''\n*Office of the Director Dockyard Division\n**Office of the Deputy Director Dockyard Division\n***Office of the Assistant Director Dockyard Division, Ships\n***Office of the Assistant Director Dockyard Division, Shore\n***Office of the Assistant Director Dockyard Division, Management Techniques\n***Office of the Assistant Director Dockyard Division, General\n***Office of the Assistant Director Dockyard Division, Nuclear\n***Office of the Assistant Director Dockyard Division, Personnel\n***Office of the Assistant Director Dockyard Division, Finance\n****Office of the Chief Constructor\n****Office of the Chief Draughtsman\n****Office of the Superintending Mechanical Engineer\n****Telecommunications Section\n****Management Training Section\n'''Fleet Maintenance Division'''\n*Office of the Director Fleet Maintenance Division\n**Office of the Deputy Director Fleet Maintenance Division\n***Office of the Assistant Director Fleet Maintenance Division\n***Office of the Assistant Director Fleet Maintenance Division, Constructive\n\n'''Marine Services Division'''\n*Office of the Director Marine Services Division\n**Office of the Deputy Marine Services Maintenance Division\n***Office of the Assistant Director Marine Services Division\n****Civil Staff Department (officer's responsible for boom defences, examiner of works, moorings, salvage, moorings)\n*****Yard Machinery District, Scottish\n*****Yard Machinery District, Northern\n*****Yard Machinery District, Midland\n*****Yard Machinery District, Southern\n'''Naval Dockyards'''<br/>\n:''Yards operating from 1860 onward during the existence of this department included.''<ref>{{cite web|title=Research guide B5: Royal Naval Dockyards|url=http://www.rmg.co.uk/discover/researchers/research-guides/research-guide-b5-royal-naval-dockyards|website=Royal Museums Greenwich UNESCO World Heritage Site In London|publisher=Royal Museums Greenwich|accessdate=1 August 2017|language=en|date=11 June 2002}}</ref>\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Antigua Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Ascension Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Bermuda Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Bombay Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Chatham Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Colombo Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Deptford Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Devonport Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Devonport Yard, NZ.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Esquimalt, Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Gibraltar Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Halifax Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Haulbowline Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Invergordon Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Jamaica Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Lyness Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Madras Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Malta Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Pembroke Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Plymouth Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Portland Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Portsmouth Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Rosyth Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Scapa Flow Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Sheerness Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Simonstown Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Singapore Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Sydney Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Trincomalee Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Wei Hai Wei Yard.]]\n*[[Royal Navy Dockyard|Woolwich Yard.]]\n\n==Timeline==\n* [[Navy Board]], Surveyor of the Navy, Dockyard Commissioners, 1546-1832\n* Board of Admiralty, Surveyor of the Navy, Dockyard Branch, 1832-1860\n* Board of Admiralty, Department of the Surveyor of Dockyards, 1872-1885\n* Board of Admiralty, Department of the Director of Dockyards, 1885-1958\n* Board of Admiralty, Dockyards and Maintenance Department, 1958-1964\n* [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]], Navy Department, Department of Dockyards and Maintenance, 1964-1968\n* [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]], Navy Department, Chief of Fleet Support Department, Department of Dockyards, 1969-1971.\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n* Archives. The National. (1690-1981) \"Records of Dockyards\". discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk. National Archives. ADM 312.\n* Brassey, Earl Thomas Allnutt (1909). Brassey's Annual: The Armed Forces Year-book. Praeger Publishers.\n*  Coats, Dr Anne; Davies, Dr David.  (2015) \"20TH CENTURY NAVAL DOCKYARDS: DEVONPORT AND PORTSMOUTH CHARACTERISATION REPORT\". Historic England. Naval Dockyards Society.\n*  Committee on Naval Affairs, United States. Congress. House (1910). Hearings on the Proposed Reorganization of the Navy Department Before the Committee on Naval Affairs of the House of Representatives [December 16, 1909 to February 17, 1910. U.S. Government Printing Office. \n* Government H.M. \"The Navy List\" (various 1869 to 1970), H.M. Stationery Office. London. England\n* Hamilton, Sir Vesey (1896). \"IV\". ''The Constitution, Character and Functions of the Board of Admiralty and the Civil Departments it Directs''. George Bell and Sons. {{ISBN|9781150465000}}.\n* Haas, J. M. (1994). ''A Management Odyssey: The Royal Dockyards, 1714-1914''. University Press of America. {{ISBN|9780819194619}}.\n* Harley, Simon; Lovell, Tony. (2016) \"Director of Dockyards and Repair (Royal Navy) - The Dreadnought Project\". dreadnoughtproject.org. Harley and Lovell' .\n* Leggett, Don (2015). Shaping the Royal Navy: Technology, Authority and Naval Architecture, C.1830-1906. Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|9780719090288}}.\n* Puddefoot, Geoff (2010). ''Ready For Anything: The Royal Fleet Auxiliary 1905-1950''. Seaforth Publishing. {{ISBN|9781848320741}}.\n* Rodger, N.A.M. (1979). ''The Admiralty. Offices of State''. Lavenham: T. Dalton. {{ISBN|0900963948}}.\n* Winfield, Rif (2014). British Warships in the Age of Sail 1817-1863: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates. Seaforth Publishing. {{ISBN| 9781473849624}}.\n\n{{Admiralty Department|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Admiralty departments]]\n[[Category:Admiralty during World War I]]\n[[Category:Admiralty during World War II]]\n[[Category:1872 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1964 disestablishments in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox government agency\n|agency_name     =  Department of the Director of Dockyards\n|motto           =\n|logo            = File:Naval Ensign of Great Britain (1707-1800).svg\n|logo_width      = 150px\n|logo_caption    = \n|seal            = \n|seal_width      =\n|seal_caption    =\n|preceding1    =  [[Surveyor of the Navy|Department of the Surveyor of the Navy]]\n|jurisdiction  = [[Government of the United Kingdom]]\n|headquarters  = [[Admiralty]]<br />[[London]]\n|formed          = 1872\n|dissolved       = 1964\n|superseding     = Dockyards and Fleet Maintenance Department\n|employees       =\n|budget          =\n|chief1_name     = Director-General of Dockyards\n|chief1_position = \n|chief2_name     = Director of Dockyards\n|chief2_position = \n|chief3_name     = Director of Fleet Maintenance\n|chief3_position = \n|chief4_name     = Director of Marine Services\n|chief4_position = \n|parent_department   = [[Admiralty]]\n|child1_agency   =\n|website         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Department of the Director of Dockyards''',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Archives|first1=The National|title=Records of Dockyards|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C721|website=discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|publisher=National Archives, 1690-1981, ADM 312|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> also known as the '''Dockyard Branch'''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Haas|first1=J. M.|title=A Management Odyssey: The Royal Dockyards, 1714-1914|date=1994|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=9780819194619|page=190|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GGIIJbXqLucC&pg=PA190&lpg=PA190&dq=Dockyard+Branch,+Admiralty&source=bl&ots=8olOJ2uydM&sig=yHU7FH0-QiwhDBOE1MZxmnVtOWA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinpvXSirXVAhWMsY8KHZ76AocQ6AEIOjAD#v=onepage&q=Dockyard%20Branch%2C%20Admiralty&f=false|language=en}}</ref> and later as the '''Dockyards and Fleet Maintenance Department''',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Archives|first1=The National|title=Director General Dockyards and Fleet Maintenance Department: report on Vote 8 Ship Drawing Offices at HM Dockyard, Chatham, Kent|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C11194424|website=discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|publisher=National Archives, 1 Jan 1961 - 31 Dec, ADM 312/4|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> was the [[Admiralty|British Admiralty department]] responsible from 1872 to 1964 for civil administration of dockyards, the building of ships, the maintenance and repair of ships at dockyards and factories, and the supervision of all civil dockyard personnel.\n\n==History==\nOriginally, responsibility for the civil management of [[Royal Navy Dockyard]]s lay with the [[Navy Board]], and in particular the [[Surveyor of the Navy]] who supervised the Navy Board's resident commissioners of the navy based at each individual yard. Following the abolition of the Navy Board in 1832, responsibility for administration of the yards passed to the [[Board of Admiralty]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Winfield|first1=Rif|title=British Warships in the Age of Sail 1817-1863: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates|date=30 April 2014|publisher=Seaforth Publishing|isbn=9781473849624|page=399|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=imFEBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA399&dq=abolition+of+the+Navy+Board+in+1832&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwie4qTFk7PVAhUYR48KHdOwDg04ChDoAQgjMAA#v=onepage&q=abolition%20of%20the%20Navy%20Board%20in%201832&f=false}}</ref> The resident commissioners were replaced by yard [[Admiral-superintendent|superintendents]], however they were primarily responsible for military administration of the yards.\n\nThe ''Surveyor of the Navy'' survived the re-organisation until 1869, when his office was merged with that of the [[Third Sea Lord|Third Naval Lord]] to become [[Controller of the Navy]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Archives|first1=The National|title=Records of the Surveyor of the Navy and successors|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C712|website=discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|publisher=National Archives, 1620-1979|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> Between 1850 and 1861, the dockyards had been subject to an investigation into management practices; the committee responsible for the investigation concluded that under the existing system was completely inefficient.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Coats|first1=Dr Anne|last2=Davies|first2=Dr David|title=20TH CENTURY NAVAL DOCKYARDS: DEVONPORT AND PORTSMOUTH CHARACTERISATION REPORT|url=https://content.historicengland.org.uk/images-books/publications/twentieth-century-naval-dockyards-devonport-portsmouth-characterisation-report/part1-twentieth-century-naval-dockyards-devonport-portsmouth-characterisation.pdf/|website=Historic England|publisher=Naval Dockyards Society, part 1, p.2, 2015|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> In 1872, to ease the burden of work on the Controller and to action reforms suggested by the inquiry, a '''Surveyor of Dockyards''' was appointed to answer these criticisms. He was originally supervised by the [[Director of Naval Construction]], who was responsible for both design and construction, and also dockyard work.\n\nIn December 1885 the post of ''Surveyor of Dockyards'' was abolished and replaced by a '''Director of Dockyards'''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brassey|first1=Earl Thomas Allnutt|title=Brassey's Annual: The Armed Forces Year-book|date=1909|publisher=Praeger Publishers|page=68}}</ref>  The new Director was instructed to visit the dockyards frequently, \"for the purpose of conferring personally with the superintendents and officers in regard to the ships and works in progress.\" <ref>{{cite book|last1=Hamilton|first1=Sir Vesey|title=The Constitution, Character and Functions of the Board of Admiralty and the Civil Departments it Directs|date=1896|publisher=George Bell and Sons|isbn=9781150465000|chapter=IV}}</ref> However, inefficiencies led to a recommendation by [[George Robinson, 1st Marquess of Ripon|George Robinson, Lord Ripon]] in which he suggested there should be a separation of the functions and duties of the naval design and construction branches, which would remain distinct from each other,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Leggett|first1=Don|title=Shaping the Royal Navy: Technology, Authority and Naval Architecture, C.1830-1906|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780719090288|page=217|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4S6hDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA218&lpg=PA218&dq=lord+ripon+admiralty+reforms&source=bl&ots=-VYrbHcOMX&sig=Oh7HLvXjJ2D4LTNDiYxHNlPBHnQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwir1pXPjLPVAhUZTo8KHQEiDwQQ6AEIPTAE#v=onepage&q=lord%20ripon%20admiralty%20reforms&f=false|language=en}}</ref> and that the branches should both coordinate and operate a sort of checks and balance system.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Leggett|first1=Don|title=Shaping the Royal Navy: Technology, Authority and Naval Architecture, C.1830-1906|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780719090288|page=217|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4S6hDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA218&lpg=PA218&dq=lord+ripon+admiralty+reforms&source=bl&ots=-VYrbHcOMX&sig=Oh7HLvXjJ2D4LTNDiYxHNlPBHnQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwir1pXPjLPVAhUZTo8KHQEiDwQQ6AEIPTAE#v=onepage&q=lord%20ripon%20admiralty%20reforms&f=false|language=en}}</ref> A set of instructions issued on 28 May 1886 communicated that the Director of Dockyards would no longer be subordinate to the Director of Naval Construction.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hamilton|first1=Sir Vesey|title=The Constitution, Character and Functions of the Board of Admiralty and the Civil Departments it Directs|date=1896|publisher=George Bell and Sons|isbn=9781150465000|chapter=IV}}</ref> Instead, he was made solely responsible to the Controller for the building of ships at dockyards, and for the maintenance and repair of ships, of boats, and of all steam machinery in ships, boats, dockyards, and factories.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Committee on Naval Affairs|first1=United States. Congress. House|title=Hearings on the Proposed Reorganization of the Navy Department Before the Committee on Naval Affairs of the House of Representatives [December 16, 1909 to February 17, 1910|date=1910|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|page=727}}</ref> In 1892 the post of Director of Dockyards was changed to ''Director of Dockyards and Works'' until 1913, when it was again renamed to ''Director of Dockyards and Repair''.\n\nDuring and after World War One, from 1917 to 1919, further restructuring with the Admiralty took place with the creation of the post of [[Deputy Controller for Dockyards and Shipbuilding]], to which the Director of Dockyards and Repairs would now report to. The department under this name would remain in place until 1957, when it was renamed '''Dockyards and Fleet Maintenance Department''' under the control of a [[Director-General]] until 1964.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Archives|first1=The National|title=Records of Dockyards|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C721|website=discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|publisher=National Archives, 1690-1981, ADM 312|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> Following the merger of the Admiralty into a new and much larger Ministry of Defence under the Navy Department, it was again renamed as the '''Department of Dockyards and Maintenance''' until 1968.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Archives|first1=The National|title=Records of Dockyards|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C721|website=discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|publisher=National Archives, 1690-1981, ADM 312|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> In 1969, overall responsibility for dockyards changed, and now came under the control of a new [[Chief Executive, Royal Dockyards]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Gordon|title=Royal Navy, including Administration, 1961-1970|url=http://www.naval-history.net/xGM-Ops-Events1961-70.htm|website=www.naval-history.net|publisher=Gordon Smith, 10 July 2011|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> who was head of the [[Royal Dockyards Management Board]].<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons 27 July 1971|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1971/jul/27/royal-dockyards|website=Hansard}}</ref>\n\n==Duties==\nA director's duties included:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hamilton|first1=Sir Vesey|title=The Constitution, Character and Functions of the Board of Admiralty and the Civil Departments it Directs|date=1896|publisher=George Bell and Sons|isbn=9781150465000|chapter=IV}}</ref>\n* assisting the Controller in the preparation of the estimates for plant and machinery required for all naval establishments;\n* exercising control of naval expenditure at all home yards;\n* exercising control of naval expenditure at all overseas yards;\n* general management of the dockyards at home and the naval yards abroad;\n* managing the economical performance of the dockyards at home and the naval yards abroad;\n* preparing annual programmes of work (subject to approval in the dockyards at home and the naval yards abroad;\n* preparing of the Navy Estimates, to determine the work to be done in the dockyards;\n* regulating the number, appropriation, and pay of the men, and the supply of necessary materials through the Director of Stores, in accordance with the approved shipbuilding programme;\n* submitting proposals relative to necessary works to be carried out in the yards by the Department of the Director of Works;\n* superintending the building of ships and boats of all classes;\n* superintending the proper maintenance and repairing of ships and their machinery, and the keeping of vessels up to the approved standard; and \n* supplying relevant machinery and appliances and provide instruction of the use of both in the yards and factories, as well as in the victualling yards.\n\n==Incumbents==\nHead of Department included:\n\n===Surveyor of Dockyards===\n* Sir Frederick Barnes, 1872 - December 1885) <ref>{{cite book|last1=Haas|first1=J. M.|title=A Management Odyssey: The Royal Dockyards, 1714-1914|date=1994|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=9780819194619|page=128|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GGIIJbXqLucC&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&dq=Admiralty,+Surveyor+of+Dockyards&source=bl&ots=8olOI4sxeP&sig=-Bwmaj9efFDcHnJL2SaHB1dHdcE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwihl6fs2LLVAhVF6Y8KHW3IBHIQ6AEIUDAG#v=onepage&q=Admiralty%2C%20Surveyor%20of%20Dockyards&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Director of Dockyards===\n* [[Sir Frederick Barnes]], December 1885 - February 1886  <ref>{{cite book|last1=Haas|first1=J. M.|title=A Management Odyssey: The Royal Dockyards, 1714-1914|date=1994|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=9780819194619|page=128|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GGIIJbXqLucC&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&dq=Admiralty,+Surveyor+of+Dockyards&source=bl&ots=8olOI4sxeP&sig=-Bwmaj9efFDcHnJL2SaHB1dHdcE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwihl6fs2LLVAhVF6Y8KHW3IBHIQ6AEIUDAG#v=onepage&q=Admiralty%2C%20Surveyor%20of%20Dockyards&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\n* Dr. [[Francis Elgar]], February 1886 - 1892 <ref>{{cite book|last1=Stationary|first1=Office|title=The Navy List|date=1888|publisher=John Murray and Son|page=301}}</ref>\n\n===Director of Dockyards and Works===\n* [[Sir James Williamson]], 1892 - July 1905) <ref>{{cite book|last1=Stationary|first1=Office|title=The Navy List|date=1892|publisher=John Murray and Son|page=349}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Haas|first1=J. M.|title=A Management Odyssey: The Royal Dockyards, 1714-1914|date=1994|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=9780819194619|page=171|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GGIIJbXqLucC&pg=PA171&dq=James+Williamson+Director+of+Dockyards&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjonrOFmbPVAhVIq48KHR7BAlkQ6AEIJDAA#v=onepage&q=James%20Williamson%20Director%20of%20Dockyards&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Sir James B. Marshall]], July 1905- March 1913 <ref>{{cite web|last1=Harley|first1=Simon|last2=Lovell|first2=Tony|title=Director of Dockyards and Repair (Royal Navy) - The Dreadnought Project|url=http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Director_of_Dockyards_and_Repair_(Royal_Navy)|website=dreadnoughtproject.org|publisher=Harley and Lovell, 18 June 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Director of Dockyards and Repair===\n* [[Sir James B. Marshall]], March 1913- April 1917 <ref>{{cite web|last1=Harley|first1=Simon|last2=Lovell|first2=Tony|title=Director of Dockyards and Repair (Royal Navy) - The Dreadnought Project|url=http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Director_of_Dockyards_and_Repair_(Royal_Navy)|website=dreadnoughtproject.org|publisher=Harley and Lovell, 18 June 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n* Vice-Admiral Sir [[Laurence Eliot Power]], 1 June 1917 \u2013 31 March 1923 <ref>{{cite web|last1=Harley|first1=Simon|last2=Lovell|first2=Tony|title=Director of Dockyards and Repair (Royal Navy) - The Dreadnought Project|url=http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Director_of_Dockyards_and_Repair_(Royal_Navy)|website=dreadnoughtproject.org|publisher=Harley and Lovell, 18 June 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n* Admiral Sir. [[Brian Barttelot|Brian H. F. Barttelot]], March, 1923 \u2013 1 March 1928 <ref>{{cite web|last1=Harley|firs